4630 /**
4631  * ring_buffer_consume - return an event and consume it
4632  * @buffer: The ring buffer to get the next event from
4633  * @cpu: the cpu to read the buffer from
4634  * @ts: a variable to store the timestamp (may be NULL)
4635  * @lost_events: a variable to store if events were lost (may be NULL)
4636  *
4637  * Returns the next event in the ring buffer, and that event is consumed.
4638  * Meaning, that sequential reads will keep returning a different event,
4639  * and eventually empty the ring buffer if the producer is slower.
4640  */
4641 struct ring_buffer_event *
4642 ring_buffer_consume(struct trace_buffer *buffer, int cpu, u64 *ts,
     /*   */
4643                     unsigned long *lost_events)
4644 {
4645         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer;
4646         struct ring_buffer_event *event = NULL;
4647         unsigned long flags;
4648         bool dolock;
4649 
4650  again:
4651         /* might be called in atomic */
4652         preempt_disable();
4653 
4654         if (!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask))
4655                 goto out;
4656 
4657         cpu_buffer = buffer->buffers[cpu];
4658         local_irq_save(flags);
4659         dolock = rb_reader_lock(cpu_buffer);
4660 
4661         event = rb_buffer_peek(cpu_buffer, ts, lost_events);
4662         if (event) {
4663                 cpu_buffer->lost_events = 0;
4664                 rb_advance_reader(cpu_buffer);
4665         }
4666 
4667         rb_reader_unlock(cpu_buffer, dolock);
4668         local_irq_restore(flags);
4669 
4670  out:
4671         preempt_enable();
4672 
4673         if (event && event->type_len == RINGBUF_TYPE_PADDING)
4674                 goto again;
4675 
4676         return event;
4677 }
4678 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_consume);

4680 /**
4681  * ring_buffer_read_prepare - Prepare for a non consuming read of the buffer
4682  * @buffer: The ring buffer to read from
4683  * @cpu: The cpu buffer to iterate over
4684  * @flags: gfp flags to use for memory allocation
4685  *
4686  * This performs the initial preparations necessary to iterate
4687  * through the buffer.  Memory is allocated, buffer recording
4688  * is disabled, and the iterator pointer is returned to the caller.
4689  *
4690  * Disabling buffer recording prevents the reading from being
4691  * corrupted. This is not a consuming read, so a producer is not
4692  * expected.
4693  *
4694  * After a sequence of ring_buffer_read_prepare calls, the user is
4695  * expected to make at least one call to ring_buffer_read_prepare_sync.
4696  * Afterwards, ring_buffer_read_start is invoked to get things going
4697  * for real.
4698  *
4699  * This overall must be paired with ring_buffer_read_finish.
4700  */
4701 struct ring_buffer_iter *
4702 ring_buffer_read_prepare(struct trace_buffer *buffer, int cpu, gfp_t flags)
     /*   */
4703 {
4704         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer;
4705         struct ring_buffer_iter *iter;
4706 
4707         if (!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask))
4708                 return NULL;
4709 
4710         iter = kzalloc(sizeof(*iter), flags);
4711         if (!iter)
4712                 return NULL;
4713 
4714         iter->event = kmalloc(BUF_MAX_DATA_SIZE, flags);
4715         if (!iter->event) {
4716                 kfree(iter);
4717                 return NULL;
4718         }
4719 
4720         cpu_buffer = buffer->buffers[cpu];
4721 
4722         iter->cpu_buffer = cpu_buffer;
4723 
4724         atomic_inc(&cpu_buffer->resize_disabled);
4725 
4726         return iter;
4727 }
4728 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_read_prepare);

4734  * iterators will be synchronized.  Afterwards, read_buffer_read_start
4735  * calls on those iterators are allowed.

4748  * This finalizes the startup of an iteration through the buffer.
4749  * The iterator comes from a call to ring_buffer_read_prepare and
4750  * an intervening ring_buffer_read_prepare_sync must have been
4751  * performed.

4753  * Must be paired with ring_buffer_read_finish.
4754  */
4755 void
4756 ring_buffer_read_start(struct ring_buffer_iter *iter)
     /*   */
4757 {

4762                 return;

4774 /**
4775  * ring_buffer_read_finish - finish reading the iterator of the buffer
4776  * @iter: The iterator retrieved by ring_buffer_start
4777  *
4778  * This re-enables the recording to the buffer, and frees the
4779  * iterator.
4780  */
4781 void
4782 ring_buffer_read_finish(struct ring_buffer_iter *iter)
     /*   */
4783 {
4784         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer = iter->cpu_buffer;
4785         unsigned long flags;
4786 
4787         /*
4788          * Ring buffer is disabled from recording, here's a good place
4789          * to check the integrity of the ring buffer.

4791          * clears the HEAD page and readers require it.

4794         rb_check_pages(cpu_buffer);
4795         raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore(&cpu_buffer->reader_lock, flags);
4796 
4797         atomic_dec(&cpu_buffer->resize_disabled);
4798         kfree(iter->event);
4799         kfree(iter);
4800 }

5037  */
5038 bool ring_buffer_empty_cpu(struct trace_buffer *buffer, int cpu)
     /*   */
5039 {
5040         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer;
5041         unsigned long flags;
5042         bool dolock;
5043         int ret;
5044 
5045         if (!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask))
5046                 return true;
5047 
5048         cpu_buffer = buffer->buffers[cpu];
5049         local_irq_save(flags);
5050         dolock = rb_reader_lock(cpu_buffer);
5051         ret = rb_per_cpu_empty(cpu_buffer);
5052         rb_reader_unlock(cpu_buffer, dolock);
5053         local_irq_restore(flags);
5054 
5055         return ret;
5056 }
5057 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_empty_cpu);

5059 #ifdef CONFIG_RING_BUFFER_ALLOW_SWAP
5060 /**
5061  * ring_buffer_swap_cpu - swap a CPU buffer between two ring buffers
5062  * @buffer_a: One buffer to swap with
5063  * @buffer_b: The other buffer to swap with
5064  * @cpu: the CPU of the buffers to swap
5065  *
5066  * This function is useful for tracers that want to take a "snapshot"
5067  * of a CPU buffer and has another back up buffer lying around.
5068  * it is expected that the tracer handles the cpu buffer not being
5069  * used at the moment.
5070  */
5071 int ring_buffer_swap_cpu(struct trace_buffer *buffer_a,
     /*   */
5072                          struct trace_buffer *buffer_b, int cpu)
5073 {
5074         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer_a;
5075         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer_b;
5076         int ret = -EINVAL;
5077 
5078         if (!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer_a->cpumask) ||
5079             !cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer_b->cpumask))
5080                 goto out;
5081 
5082         cpu_buffer_a = buffer_a->buffers[cpu];
5083         cpu_buffer_b = buffer_b->buffers[cpu];
5084 
5085         /* At least make sure the two buffers are somewhat the same */
5086         if (cpu_buffer_a->nr_pages != cpu_buffer_b->nr_pages)
5087                 goto out;
5088 
5089         ret = -EAGAIN;
5090 
5091         if (atomic_read(&buffer_a->record_disabled))
5092                 goto out;
5093 
5094         if (atomic_read(&buffer_b->record_disabled))
5095                 goto out;
5096 
5097         if (atomic_read(&cpu_buffer_a->record_disabled))
5098                 goto out;
5099 
5100         if (atomic_read(&cpu_buffer_b->record_disabled))
5101                 goto out;
5102 
5103         /*
5104          * We can't do a synchronize_rcu here because this
5105          * function can be called in atomic context.
5106          * Normally this will be called from the same CPU as cpu.
5107          * If not it's up to the caller to protect this.
5108          */
5109         atomic_inc(&cpu_buffer_a->record_disabled);
5110         atomic_inc(&cpu_buffer_b->record_disabled);
5111 
5112         ret = -EBUSY;
5113         if (local_read(&cpu_buffer_a->committing))
5114                 goto out_dec;
5115         if (local_read(&cpu_buffer_b->committing))
5116                 goto out_dec;
5117 
5118         buffer_a->buffers[cpu] = cpu_buffer_b;
5119         buffer_b->buffers[cpu] = cpu_buffer_a;
5120 
5121         cpu_buffer_b->buffer = buffer_a;
5122         cpu_buffer_a->buffer = buffer_b;
5123 
5124         ret = 0;
5125 
5126 out_dec:
5127         atomic_dec(&cpu_buffer_a->record_disabled);
5128         atomic_dec(&cpu_buffer_b->record_disabled);
5129 out:
5130         return ret;
5131 }
5132 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_swap_cpu);
5133 #endif /* CONFIG_RING_BUFFER_ALLOW_SWAP */

5135 /**
5136  * ring_buffer_alloc_read_page - allocate a page to read from buffer
5137  * @buffer: the buffer to allocate for.
5138  * @cpu: the cpu buffer to allocate.
5139  *
5140  * This function is used in conjunction with ring_buffer_read_page.
5141  * When reading a full page from the ring buffer, these functions
5142  * can be used to speed up the process. The calling function should
5143  * allocate a few pages first with this function. Then when it
5144  * needs to get pages from the ring buffer, it passes the result
5145  * of this function into ring_buffer_read_page, which will swap
5146  * the page that was allocated, with the read page of the buffer.
5147  *
5148  * Returns:
5149  *  The page allocated, or ERR_PTR
5150  */
5151 void *ring_buffer_alloc_read_page(struct trace_buffer *buffer, int cpu)
     /*   */
5152 {
5153         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer;
5154         struct buffer_data_page *bpage = NULL;
5155         unsigned long flags;
5156         struct page *page;
5157 
5158         if (!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask))
5159                 return ERR_PTR(-ENODEV);
5160 
5161         cpu_buffer = buffer->buffers[cpu];
5162         local_irq_save(flags);
5163         arch_spin_lock(&cpu_buffer->lock);
5164 
5165         if (cpu_buffer->free_page) {
5166                 bpage = cpu_buffer->free_page;
5167                 cpu_buffer->free_page = NULL;
5168         }
5169 
5170         arch_spin_unlock(&cpu_buffer->lock);
5171         local_irq_restore(flags);
5172 
5173         if (bpage)
5174                 goto out;
5175 
5176         page = alloc_pages_node(cpu_to_node(cpu),
5177                                 GFP_KERNEL | __GFP_NORETRY, 0);
5178         if (!page)
5179                 return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
5180 
5181         bpage = page_address(page);
5182 
5183  out:
5184         rb_init_page(bpage);
5185 
5186         return bpage;
5187 }
5188 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_alloc_read_page);
5189 
5190 /**
5191  * ring_buffer_free_read_page - free an allocated read page
5192  * @buffer: the buffer the page was allocate for
5193  * @cpu: the cpu buffer the page came from
5194  * @data: the page to free
5195  *
5196  * Free a page allocated from ring_buffer_alloc_read_page.
5197  */
5198 void ring_buffer_free_read_page(struct trace_buffer *buffer, int cpu, void *data)
     /*   */
5199 {
5200         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer = buffer->buffers[cpu];
5201         struct buffer_data_page *bpage = data;
5202         struct page *page = virt_to_page(bpage);
5203         unsigned long flags;
5204 
5205         /* If the page is still in use someplace else, we can't reuse it */
5206         if (page_ref_count(page) > 1)
5207                 goto out;
5208 
5209         local_irq_save(flags);
5210         arch_spin_lock(&cpu_buffer->lock);
5211 
5212         if (!cpu_buffer->free_page) {
5213                 cpu_buffer->free_page = bpage;
5214                 bpage = NULL;
5215         }
5216 
5217         arch_spin_unlock(&cpu_buffer->lock);
5218         local_irq_restore(flags);
5219 
5220  out:
5221         free_page((unsigned long)bpage);
5222 }
5223 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_free_read_page);
5224 
5225 /**
5226  * ring_buffer_read_page - extract a page from the ring buffer
5227  * @buffer: buffer to extract from
5228  * @data_page: the page to use allocated from ring_buffer_alloc_read_page
5229  * @len: amount to extract
5230  * @cpu: the cpu of the buffer to extract
5231  * @full: should the extraction only happen when the page is full.
5232  *
5233  * This function will pull out a page from the ring buffer and consume it.
5234  * @data_page must be the address of the variable that was returned
5235  * from ring_buffer_alloc_read_page. This is because the page might be used
5236  * to swap with a page in the ring buffer.
5237  *
5238  * for example:
5239  *      rpage = ring_buffer_alloc_read_page(buffer, cpu);
5240  *      if (IS_ERR(rpage))
5241  *              return PTR_ERR(rpage);
5242  *      ret = ring_buffer_read_page(buffer, &rpage, len, cpu, 0);
5243  *      if (ret >= 0)
5244  *              process_page(rpage, ret);
5245  *
5246  * When @full is set, the function will not return true unless
5247  * the writer is off the reader page.
5248  *
5249  * Note: it is up to the calling functions to handle sleeps and wakeups.
5250  *  The ring buffer can be used anywhere in the kernel and can not
5251  *  blindly call wake_up. The layer that uses the ring buffer must be
5252  *  responsible for that.
5253  *
5254  * Returns:
5255  *  >=0 if data has been transferred, returns the offset of consumed data.
5256  *  <0 if no data has been transferred.
5257  */
5258 int ring_buffer_read_page(struct trace_buffer *buffer,
     /*   */
5259                           void **data_page, size_t len, int cpu, int full)
5260 {
5261         struct ring_buffer_per_cpu *cpu_buffer = buffer->buffers[cpu];
5262         struct ring_buffer_event *event;
5263         struct buffer_data_page *bpage;
5264         struct buffer_page *reader;
5265         unsigned long missed_events;
5266         unsigned long flags;
5267         unsigned int commit;
5268         unsigned int read;
5269         u64 save_timestamp;
5270         int ret = -1;
5271 
5272         if (!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask))
5273                 goto out;
5274 
5275         /*
5276          * If len is not big enough to hold the page header, then
5277          * we can not copy anything.
5278          */
5279         if (len <= BUF_PAGE_HDR_SIZE)
5280                 goto out;
5281 
5282         len -= BUF_PAGE_HDR_SIZE;
5283 
5284         if (!data_page)
5285                 goto out;
5286 
5287         bpage = *data_page;
5288         if (!bpage)
5289                 goto out;
5290 
5291         raw_spin_lock_irqsave(&cpu_buffer->reader_lock, flags);
5292 
5293         reader = rb_get_reader_page(cpu_buffer);
5294         if (!reader)
5295                 goto out_unlock;
5296 
5297         event = rb_reader_event(cpu_buffer);
5298 
5299         read = reader->read;
5300         commit = rb_page_commit(reader);
5301 
5302         /* Check if any events were dropped */
5303         missed_events = cpu_buffer->lost_events;
5304 
5305         /*
5306          * If this page has been partially read or
5307          * if len is not big enough to read the rest of the page or
5308          * a writer is still on the page, then
5309          * we must copy the data from the page to the buffer.
5310          * Otherwise, we can simply swap the page with the one passed in.
5311          */
5312         if (read || (len < (commit - read)) ||
5313             cpu_buffer->reader_page == cpu_buffer->commit_page) {
5314                 struct buffer_data_page *rpage = cpu_buffer->reader_page->page;
5315                 unsigned int rpos = read;
5316                 unsigned int pos = 0;
5317                 unsigned int size;
5318 
5319                 if (full)
5320                         goto out_unlock;
5321 
5322                 if (len > (commit - read))
5323                         len = (commit - read);
5324 
5325                 /* Always keep the time extend and data together */
5326                 size = rb_event_ts_length(event);
5327 
5328                 if (len < size)
5329                         goto out_unlock;
5330 
5331                 /* save the current timestamp, since the user will need it */
5332                 save_timestamp = cpu_buffer->read_stamp;
5333 
5334                 /* Need to copy one event at a time */
5335                 do {
5336                         /* We need the size of one event, because
5337                          * rb_advance_reader only advances by one event,
5338                          * whereas rb_event_ts_length may include the size of
5339                          * one or two events.
5340                          * We have already ensured there's enough space if this
5341                          * is a time extend. */
5342                         size = rb_event_length(event);
5343                         memcpy(bpage->data + pos, rpage->data + rpos, size);
5344 
5345                         len -= size;
5346 
5347                         rb_advance_reader(cpu_buffer);
5348                         rpos = reader->read;
5349                         pos += size;
5350 
5351                         if (rpos >= commit)
5352                                 break;
5353 
5354                         event = rb_reader_event(cpu_buffer);
5355                         /* Always keep the time extend and data together */
5356                         size = rb_event_ts_length(event);
5357                 } while (len >= size);
5358 
5359                 /* update bpage */
5360                 local_set(&bpage->commit, pos);
5361                 bpage->time_stamp = save_timestamp;
5362 
5363                 /* we copied everything to the beginning */
5364                 read = 0;
5365         } else {
5366                 /* update the entry counter */
5367                 cpu_buffer->read += rb_page_entries(reader);
5368                 cpu_buffer->read_bytes += BUF_PAGE_SIZE;
5369 
5370                 /* swap the pages */
5371                 rb_init_page(bpage);
5372                 bpage = reader->page;
5373                 reader->page = *data_page;
5374                 local_set(&reader->write, 0);
5375                 local_set(&reader->entries, 0);
5376                 reader->read = 0;
5377                 *data_page = bpage;
5378 
5379                 /*
5380                  * Use the real_end for the data size,
5381                  * This gives us a chance to store the lost events
5382                  * on the page.
5383                  */
5384                 if (reader->real_end)
5385                         local_set(&bpage->commit, reader->real_end);
5386         }
5387         ret = read;
5388 
5389         cpu_buffer->lost_events = 0;
5390 
5391         commit = local_read(&bpage->commit);
5392         /*
5393          * Set a flag in the commit field if we lost events
5394          */
5395         if (missed_events) {
5396                 /* If there is room at the end of the page to save the
5397                  * missed events, then record it there.
5398                  */
5399                 if (BUF_PAGE_SIZE - commit >= sizeof(missed_events)) {
5400                         memcpy(&bpage->data[commit], &missed_events,
5401                                sizeof(missed_events));
5402                         local_add(RB_MISSED_STORED, &bpage->commit);
5403                         commit += sizeof(missed_events);
5404                 }
5405                 local_add(RB_MISSED_EVENTS, &bpage->commit);
5406         }
5407 
5408         /*
5409          * This page may be off to user land. Zero it out here.
5410          */
5411         if (commit < BUF_PAGE_SIZE)
5412                 memset(&bpage->data[commit], 0, BUF_PAGE_SIZE - commit);
5413 
5414  out_unlock:
5415         raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore(&cpu_buffer->reader_lock, flags);
5416 
5417  out:
5418         return ret;
5419 }
5420 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ring_buffer_read_page);

5422 /*
5423  * We only allocate new buffers, never free them if the CPU goes down.
5424  * If we were to free the buffer, then the user would lose any trace that was in
5425  * the buffer.
5426  */
5427 int trace_rb_cpu_prepare(unsigned int cpu, struct hlist_node *node)
     /*   */
5428 {
5429         struct trace_buffer *buffer;
5430         long nr_pages_same;
5431         int cpu_i;
5432         unsigned long nr_pages;
5433 
5434         buffer = container_of(node, struct trace_buffer, node);
5435         if (cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask))
5436                 return 0;
5437 
5438         nr_pages = 0;
5439         nr_pages_same = 1;
5440         /* check if all cpu sizes are same */
5441         for_each_buffer_cpu(buffer, cpu_i) {
5442                 /* fill in the size from first enabled cpu */
5443                 if (nr_pages == 0)
5444                         nr_pages = buffer->buffers[cpu_i]->nr_pages;
5445                 if (nr_pages != buffer->buffers[cpu_i]->nr_pages) {
5446                         nr_pages_same = 0;
5447                         break;
5448                 }
5449         }
5450         /* allocate minimum pages, user can later expand it */
5451         if (!nr_pages_same)
5452                 nr_pages = 2;
5453         buffer->buffers[cpu] =
5454                 rb_allocate_cpu_buffer(buffer, nr_pages, cpu);
5455         if (!buffer->buffers[cpu]) {
5456                 WARN(1, "failed to allocate ring buffer on CPU %u\n",
5457                      cpu);
5458                 return -ENOMEM;
5459         }
5460         smp_wmb();
5461         cpumask_set_cpu(cpu, buffer->cpumask);
5462         return 0;
5463 }

5465 #ifdef CONFIG_RING_BUFFER_STARTUP_TEST
5466 /*
5467  * This is a basic integrity check of the ring buffer.
5468  * Late in the boot cycle this test will run when configured in.
5469  * It will kick off a thread per CPU that will go into a loop
5470  * writing to the per cpu ring buffer various sizes of data.
5471  * Some of the data will be large items, some small.
5472  *
5473  * Another thread is created that goes into a spin, sending out
5474  * IPIs to the other CPUs to also write into the ring buffer.
5475  * this is to test the nesting ability of the buffer.
5476  *
5477  * Basic stats are recorded and reported. If something in the
5478  * ring buffer should happen that's not expected, a big warning
5479  * is displayed and all ring buffers are disabled.
5480  */
5481 static struct task_struct *rb_threads[NR_CPUS] __initdata;
5482 
5483 struct rb_test_data {
5484         struct trace_buffer *buffer;
5485         unsigned long           events;
5486         unsigned long           bytes_written;
5487         unsigned long           bytes_alloc;
5488         unsigned long           bytes_dropped;
5489         unsigned long           events_nested;
5490         unsigned long           bytes_written_nested;
5491         unsigned long           bytes_alloc_nested;
5492         unsigned long           bytes_dropped_nested;
5493         int                     min_size_nested;
5494         int                     max_size_nested;
5495         int                     max_size;
5496         int                     min_size;
5497         int                     cpu;
5498         int                     cnt;
5499 };
5500 
5501 static struct rb_test_data rb_data[NR_CPUS] __initdata;
5502 
5503 /* 1 meg per cpu */
5504 #define RB_TEST_BUFFER_SIZE     1048576
5505 
5506 static char rb_string[] __initdata =
5507         "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz1234567890!@#$%^&*()?+\\"
5508         "?+|:';\",.<>/?abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz1234567890"
5509         "!@#$%^&*()?+\\?+|:';\",.<>/?abcdefghijklmnopqrstuv";
5510 
5511 static bool rb_test_started __initdata;
5512 
5513 struct rb_item {
5514         int size;
5515         char str[];
5516 };
5517 
5518 static __init int rb_write_something(struct rb_test_data *data, bool nested)
     /*   */
5519 {
5520         struct ring_buffer_event *event;
5521         struct rb_item *item;
5522         bool started;
5523         int event_len;
5524         int size;
5525         int len;
5526         int cnt;
5527 
5528         /* Have nested writes different that what is written */
5529         cnt = data->cnt + (nested ? 27 : 0);
5530 
5531         /* Multiply cnt by ~e, to make some unique increment */
5532         size = (cnt * 68 / 25) % (sizeof(rb_string) - 1);
5533 
5534         len = size + sizeof(struct rb_item);
5535 
5536         started = rb_test_started;
5537         /* read rb_test_started before checking buffer enabled */
5538         smp_rmb();
5539 
5540         event = ring_buffer_lock_reserve(data->buffer, len);
5541         if (!event) {
5542                 /* Ignore dropped events before test starts. */
5543                 if (started) {
5544                         if (nested)
5545                                 data->bytes_dropped += len;
5546                         else
5547                                 data->bytes_dropped_nested += len;
5548                 }
5549                 return len;
5550         }
5551 
5552         event_len = ring_buffer_event_length(event);
5553 
5554         if (RB_WARN_ON(data->buffer, event_len < len))
5555                 goto out;
5556 
5557         item = ring_buffer_event_data(event);
5558         item->size = size;
5559         memcpy(item->str, rb_string, size);
5560 
5561         if (nested) {
5562                 data->bytes_alloc_nested += event_len;
5563                 data->bytes_written_nested += len;
5564                 data->events_nested++;
5565                 if (!data->min_size_nested || len < data->min_size_nested)
5566                         data->min_size_nested = len;
5567                 if (len > data->max_size_nested)
5568                         data->max_size_nested = len;
5569         } else {
5570                 data->bytes_alloc += event_len;
5571                 data->bytes_written += len;
5572                 data->events++;
5573                 if (!data->min_size || len < data->min_size)
5574                         data->max_size = len;
5575                 if (len > data->max_size)
5576                         data->max_size = len;
5577         }
5578 
5579  out:
5580         ring_buffer_unlock_commit(data->buffer, event);
5581 
5582         return 0;
5583 }

5585 static __init int rb_test(void *arg)
     /*   */
5586 {
5587         struct rb_test_data *data = arg;
5588 
5589         while (!kthread_should_stop()) {
5590                 rb_write_something(data, false);
5591                 data->cnt++;
5592

5594                 /* Now sleep between a min of 100-300us and a max of 1ms */
5595                 usleep_range(((data->cnt % 3) + 1) * 100, 1000);
5596         }
5597 
5598         return 0;

5623 static __init int test_ringbuffer(void)
     /*   */
5624 {
5625         struct task_struct *rb_hammer;
5626         struct trace_buffer *buffer;
5627         int cpu;
5628         int ret = 0;
5629 
5630         if (security_locked_down(LOCKDOWN_TRACEFS)) {
5631                 pr_warn("Lockdown is enabled, skipping ring buffer tests\n");
5632                 return 0;
5633         }
5634 
5635         pr_info("Running ring buffer tests...\n");
5636 
5637         buffer = ring_buffer_alloc(RB_TEST_BUFFER_SIZE, RB_FL_OVERWRITE);
5638         if (WARN_ON(!buffer))
5639                 return 0;
5640 
5641         /* Disable buffer so that threads can't write to it yet */
5642         ring_buffer_record_off(buffer);
5643 
5644         for_each_online_cpu(cpu) {
5645                 rb_data[cpu].buffer = buffer;
5646                 rb_data[cpu].cpu = cpu;
5647                 rb_data[cpu].cnt = cpu;
5648                 rb_threads[cpu] = kthread_create(rb_test, &rb_data[cpu],
5649                                                  "rbtester/%d", cpu);
5650                 if (WARN_ON(IS_ERR(rb_threads[cpu]))) {
5651                         pr_cont("FAILED\n");
5652                         ret = PTR_ERR(rb_threads[cpu]);
5653                         goto out_free;
5654                 }
5655 
5656                 kthread_bind(rb_threads[cpu], cpu);
5657                 wake_up_process(rb_threads[cpu]);
5658         }
5659 
5660         /* Now create the rb hammer! */
5661         rb_hammer = kthread_run(rb_hammer_test, NULL, "rbhammer");
5662         if (WARN_ON(IS_ERR(rb_hammer))) {
5663                 pr_cont("FAILED\n");
5664                 ret = PTR_ERR(rb_hammer);
5665                 goto out_free;
5666         }
5667 
5668         ring_buffer_record_on(buffer);
5669         /*
5670          * Show buffer is enabled before setting rb_test_started.
5671          * Yes there's a small race window where events could be
5672          * dropped and the thread wont catch it. But when a ring
5673          * buffer gets enabled, there will always be some kind of
5674          * delay before other CPUs see it. Thus, we don't care about
5675          * those dropped events. We care about events dropped after
5676          * the threads see that the buffer is active.
5677          */
5678         smp_wmb();
5679         rb_test_started = true;
5680 
5681         set_current_state(TASK_INTERRUPTIBLE);
5682         /* Just run for 10 seconds */;
5683         schedule_timeout(10 * HZ);
5684 
5685         kthread_stop(rb_hammer);
5686 
5687  out_free:
5688         for_each_online_cpu(cpu) {
5689                 if (!rb_threads[cpu])
5690                         break;
5691                 kthread_stop(rb_threads[cpu]);
5692         }
5693         if (ret) {
5694                 ring_buffer_free(buffer);
5695                 return ret;
5696         }
5697 
5698         /* Report! */
5699         pr_info("finished\n");
5700         for_each_online_cpu(cpu) {
5701                 struct ring_buffer_event *event;
5702                 struct rb_test_data *data = &rb_data[cpu];
5703                 struct rb_item *item;
5704                 unsigned long total_events;
5705                 unsigned long total_dropped;
5706                 unsigned long total_written;
5707                 unsigned long total_alloc;
5708                 unsigned long total_read = 0;
5709                 unsigned long total_size = 0;
5710                 unsigned long total_len = 0;
5711                 unsigned long total_lost = 0;
5712                 unsigned long lost;
5713                 int big_event_size;
5714                 int small_event_size;
5715 
5716                 ret = -1;
5717 
5718                 total_events = data->events + data->events_nested;
5719                 total_written = data->bytes_written + data->bytes_written_nested;
5720                 total_alloc = data->bytes_alloc + data->bytes_alloc_nested;
5721                 total_dropped = data->bytes_dropped + data->bytes_dropped_nested;
5722 
5723                 big_event_size = data->max_size + data->max_size_nested;
5724                 small_event_size = data->min_size + data->min_size_nested;
5725 
5726                 pr_info("CPU %d:\n", cpu);
5727                 pr_info("              events:    %ld\n", total_events);
5728                 pr_info("       dropped bytes:    %ld\n", total_dropped);
5729                 pr_info("       alloced bytes:    %ld\n", total_alloc);
5730                 pr_info("       written bytes:    %ld\n", total_written);
5731                 pr_info("       biggest event:    %d\n", big_event_size);
5732                 pr_info("      smallest event:    %d\n", small_event_size);
5733 
5734                 if (RB_WARN_ON(buffer, total_dropped))
5735                         break;
5736 
5737                 ret = 0;
5738 
5739                 while ((event = ring_buffer_consume(buffer, cpu, NULL, &lost))) {
5740                         total_lost += lost;
5741                         item = ring_buffer_event_data(event);
5742                         total_len += ring_buffer_event_length(event);
5743                         total_size += item->size + sizeof(struct rb_item);
5744                         if (memcmp(&item->str[0], rb_string, item->size) != 0) {
5745                                 pr_info("FAILED!\n");
5746                                 pr_info("buffer had: %.*s\n", item->size, item->str);
5747                                 pr_info("expected:   %.*s\n", item->size, rb_string);
5748                                 RB_WARN_ON(buffer, 1);
5749                                 ret = -1;
5750                                 break;
5751                         }
5752                         total_read++;
5753                 }
5754                 if (ret)
5755                         break;
5756 
5757                 ret = -1;
5758 
5759                 pr_info("         read events:   %ld\n", total_read);
5760                 pr_info("         lost events:   %ld\n", total_lost);
5761                 pr_info("        total events:   %ld\n", total_lost + total_read);
5762                 pr_info("  recorded len bytes:   %ld\n", total_len);
5763                 pr_info(" recorded size bytes:   %ld\n", total_size);
5764                 if (total_lost)
5765                         pr_info(" With dropped events, record len and size may not match\n"
5766                                 " alloced and written from above\n");
5767                 if (!total_lost) {
5768                         if (RB_WARN_ON(buffer, total_len != total_alloc ||
5769                                        total_size != total_written))
5770                                 break;
5771                 }
5772                 if (RB_WARN_ON(buffer, total_lost + total_read != total_events))
5773                         break;
5774 
5775                 ret = 0;
5776         }
5777         if (!ret)
5778                 pr_info("Ring buffer PASSED!\n");
5779 
5780         ring_buffer_free(buffer);
5781         return 0;
5782 }
5783 
5784 late_initcall(test_ringbuffer);
5785 #endif /* CONFIG_RING_BUFFER_STARTUP_TEST */
